'''''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo''''' is a 2011 American [[Thriller (genre)|thriller film]]. Based on the [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo|novel of the same name]] by [[Stieg Larsson]], the film adaptation was directed by [[David Fincher]] and written by [[Steven Zaillian]]. [[Atticus Ross]] and [[Trent Reznor]] provided the soundtrack. The film stars [[Daniel Craig]] and [[Rooney Mara]] and tells the story of journalist Mikael Blomqvist's (Craig) mission to find out what happened to a woman who had disappeared over forty years before. He works with the help of computer hacker Lisbeth Salander (Mara).

A concerted effort by [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] associates [[Michael Lynton]] and [[Amy Pascal]] to create the film started in 2009. It took the company a few months to obtain rights to the novel, during which they recruited Zaillian and Fincher. The casting process for the lead roles was exhaustive and intense; Craig initially faced scheduling conflicts, while a plethora of actresses sought the role of Lisbeth Salander. The film's script took over six months to write, which included three months of analyzing the novel. With a production budget of $90 million, filming took place in Sweden, Switzerland and Norway over seven months.

Pre-release screenings occurred in London, New York City, and Stockholm. Critics positively reviewed the film, applauding its dark, grim tone. Mara and Craig's performances also received kudos from commentators. The film garnered $232.6 million over its theatrical run. In addition to being included in the best-of lists in several publications, the film was a candidate for numerous awards, ultimately winning seven accolades including an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]].

== Synopsis ==
Mikael Blomkvist ([[Daniel Craig]]), co-owner of ''Millennium'' magazine, has just lost a [[libel]] case brought against him by crooked businessman Hans-Erik Wennerstr<U+00F6>m ([[Ulf Friberg]]).  Lisbeth Salander ([[Rooney Mara]]), a damaged but brilliant researcher and computer hacker, compiled an extensive background check on Blomkvist for Swedish magnate Henrik Vanger ([[Christopher Plummer]]), who has a special task for him. In exchange for the promise of damning information about Wennerstr<U+00F6>m, Blomkvist agrees to move into a cabin at the Vanger estate to investigate the disappearance and assumed murder of Henrik's grandniece, Harriet, 40 years before. Blomkvist uncovers a notebook containing a list of names and numbers that no one has been able to decipher.

Salander, who is under state legal guardianship due to mental incompetency, is appointed a new guardian, lawyer Nils Bjurman ([[Yorick van Wageningen]]). He abuses his authority to extort sexual favors from Salander and then forcibly rapes her, not realizing she has a hidden video camera in her bag. She regains control of her life by [[blackmail]]ing Bjurman, after stunning him with a [[taser]], raping him with a [[dildo]], and marking him as a rapist with a [[tattoo]] on his chest and stomach.

Blomkvist's daughter visits him and notes that the numbers from the notebook are bible references. Blomkvist tells Vanger's lieutenant that he needs help with his research, and he recommends Salander based on the great work she did researching Blomkvist himself. Surprised, he hires Salander to further investigate the notebook's content. She uncovers a connection to a series of murders of young Jewish women that occurred from 1947 through 1967, causing Blomkvist to mention that the Vangers are known [[antisemitism|antisemites]]. During the investigation, Salander and Blomkvist become lovers. Henrik's brother Harald ([[Per Myrberg]]) identifies Martin ([[Stellan Skarsg<U+00E5>rd]]), Harriet's brother and operational head of the Vanger empire, as a possible suspect. Blomkvist and Salander continue their research, with Salander uncovering connections between the series of murders, Martin Vanger's father and Martin himself.

Blomkvist breaks into Martin's house to look for more clues, but Martin catches him and prepares to kill him. Martin brags about his crimes, but denies killing Harriet. Salander arrives, subdues Martin and saves Blomkvist. While Salander tends to Blomkvist, Martin flees. Salander, on her motorcycle, pursues Martin in his SUV. He loses control of his vehicle on an icy road and dies when it catches fire. As more secrets are revealed about the Vanger family, Blomkvist deduces that Harriet has been helped by other Vanger family members with a false identity and a move outside Sweden to hide from Martin. Blomkvist confronts Harriet, who describes generations of abuse within the Vanger family and Martin's knowledge of her involvement in her father's death. Finally free of her brother, thanks to Salander and Blomkvist, she returns to Sweden and tearfully reunites with Henrik.

As promised, Henrik gives Blomkvist the information on Wennerstr<U+00F6>m, but it is not helpful. Salander responds by hacking Wennerstr<U+00F6>m's computer and presenting Blomkvist with incriminating information about his activities. This evidence vindicates ''Millennium'' and destroys Wennerstr<U+00F6>m. Salander hacks into Wennerstr<U+00F6>m's bank accounts and transfers two billion [[euros]] to her own secret accounts. During this time, Wennerstr<U+00F6>m is murdered. Salander reveals to her friend, and former guardian, that she has made a connection with Blomkvist. On her way to give Blomkvist a specially chosen Christmas present, Salander sees him and his longtime lover and business partner Erika Berger ([[Robin Wright]]) walking together happily. She discards the gift and rides away.

== Cast ==
[[File:Skyfall's cast and crew arrive on location in Istanbul (7).jpg|thumb|Fincher admired Craig's ability to adapt into the role of Mikael Blomkvist.<ref name=filming/>]]

* [[Daniel Craig]] as [[Mikael Blomkvist]]
:A co-owner for Swedish lifestyle magazine ''Millennium'', Blomkvist is devoted to exposing the corruptions and malfeasances of government, attracting infamy for his tendency to "go too far".<ref name=filming>{{cite web|url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies_2011/girl_with_dragon/notes.pdf|title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo: Production Notes|format=PDF|publisher=Visual Hollywood|date=|accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Craig competed with [[Brad Pitt]] and [[George Clooney]] as candidates for the role.<ref name=entd3>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/06/17/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo/|title=This week's cover: The secrets of 'The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo'|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=June 17, 2010|accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref><ref name=hollzgirl>{{cite web | last=Kilday | first=Greg | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-rooney-mara-281904| title=The Making of 'The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo'| work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]| date=January 24, 2012|accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> Initial concerns over schedule conflicts with the production of ''[[Cowboys & Aliens]]'' (2011) and ''[[Skyfall]]'' (2012) prompted Craig to postpone the casting process.<ref name=hollzgirl/><ref name=deadline/> Given the uncertainty surrounding ''Skyfall'' following [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]'s bankruptcy, [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] and [[DreamWorks]] worked out a schedule and Craig agreed to take the part.<ref name=deadline>{{cite news |last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/07/daniel-craig-closes-deal-for-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo |title=Daniel Craig Closes Deal For 'The Girl with The Dragon Tattoo' |publisher=[[Deadline]] |date=July 26, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> The British actor was required to gain weight and adopted a neutral accent to befit Stockholm's cosmopolitan lifestyle. "I went for something very plain," he explained. "David and I talked about it and we both didn't want an accent to get in the way of the character. Really, many Swedes speak incredibly good English, both with and without accents. I just felt that was the way to go. Blomkvist is well traveled, he's been all over the world, he's been listening to the BBC since he was six and I think this is the person he is." Craig spoke about the film's source material amid the "initial craze"; "It's one of those books you just don't put down. There's just this immediate feeling that bad things are going to happen and I think that's part of why they've been so readable for people."<ref name=filming/>
* [[Rooney Mara]] as [[Lisbeth Salander]]
{{Quote box |bgcolor=#ffeeaa |salign=right |width=240px |align=right |quote=What endeared me to her [Mara] during the audition process was exactly what I wanted from Lisbeth: she doesn't quit. I wanted that person who was indomitable. By the end of our casting process, I knew this was someone worth falling on the grenade for. |source={{mdash}}[[David Fincher]]<ref name=filming/>}}

:The [[Audrey Hepburn]]-esque heroine, as described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic [[Michiko Kakutani]], Salander is a computer hacker who is the victim of mental and sexual abuse. The character was a "vulnerable victim turned vigilante" who possessed the "take-no-prisoners" attitude of [[Lara Croft]] and the "cool, unsentimental intellect" of [[Spock]], according to Kakutani. Fincher felt that Salander's eccentric persona was enthralling. "There's a kind of wish fulfillment to her in the way that she takes care of things, the way she will only put up with so much, but there are other sides to her as well," he professed.<ref name=filming/> Casting was complicated by the raft of prominent candidates such as [[Natalie Portman]], [[Ellen Page]], [[Kristen Stewart]], [[Keira Knightley]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Olivia Thirlby]], [[Scarlett Johansson]], and [[Emma Watson]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ditzian |first=Eric |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645813/rooney-mara-lands-lead-girl-with-dragon-tattoo.jhtml |title=Rooney Mara Lands Lead In 'Girl with The Dragon Tattoo' |publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom]]) |date=August 16, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ditzian |first=Eric |url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2010/07/21/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-casting-rumors-sizing-up-our-potential-lisbeth-salander/|title='The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo' Casting Rumors: Sizing Up Our Potential Lisbeth Salander|publisher=MTV (Viacom) |date=July 27, 2010 |accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> Despite the hype, some eventually withdrew from consideration due to the time commitment and low pay.<ref name="DailyBeast">{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2010-08-15/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-who-will-play-her |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo: Who Will Play Her? |last=Piccalo |first=Gina |work=[[The Daily Beast]]|publisher=[[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]] |date=August 15, 2010 |accessdate=December 14, 2010}}</ref> Mara had worked with Fincher in his 2010 film ''[[The Social Network]]''.<ref name=hollzgirl/><ref name=filming/> Fincher found it difficult at first to mold the actress to match Salanders' antisocial demeanor, which was a vast contrast from her earlier role as the submissive Erica.<ref name=hollzgirl/> Mara went through multiple changes in her appearance to become Salander: her hair, for instance, was dyed black and cut into various jagged points, giving the illusion that she cut it herself.<ref name=wmag>{{cite web |last=Hirschberg |first=Lynn |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2011/02/rooney_mara_girl_with_the_dragon_tattoo_film|title=David Fincher Gets The Girl|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]] |date=February 2011|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> In addition to her transgressive appearance<U+2014>one that was described as a "mash-up of brazen Seventies punk and spooky Eighties goth with a dash of [[Sadomasochism|S&M]] temptress" by Lynn Hirschberg of ''[[W (magazine)|W]]''<ref name=wmag/><U+2014>the actress participated in a formal screening and was filmed by Fincher on a subway in [[Los Angeles, California]] in an effort to persuade the executives of Sony Pictures that she was a credible choice.<ref name=hollzgirl/>
* [[Yorick van Wageningen]] as Nils Bjurman
:Salander's new legal guardian, Bjurman abuses her to gain control, an atrocity that the character began following a glimpse of her records. Fincher wanted the character to be worse than a typical antagonist, although he didn't want to emulate the stereotypical "mustache-twirling pervert". The director considered van Wageningen to be the embodiment of a versatile actor<U+2014>one that was a "full-fledged human being", a "brilliant" actor. "He was able to bring his performance from a logical place in Bjurman's mind and find the seething morass of darkness inside," Fincher stated. Bjurman's multi-faceted psyche was the main reason van Wageningen wanted to play the role. The Dutch actor said, "This character goes through a lot and I wasn't quite sure I wanted to go through all that. I started out half way between the elation of getting to work with David Fincher and the dread of this character, but I was able to use both of those things. We both thought the most interesting route would be for Bjurman to seem half affable. The challenge was not in finding the freak violence in the guy but finding the humanity of him."<ref name=filming/>
* [[Christopher Plummer]] as Henrik Vanger
:Henrik is an established businessman who launches an extensive investigation into his family's affairs. Despite calling the Vanger family "dysfunctional", Plummer said of the character: "I love the character of the old man, and I sympathize with him. He's really the nicest old guy in the whole book. Everybody is a bit suspect, and still are at the end. Old Vanger has a nice straight line, and he gets his wish."<ref>{{cite web |last=Rocchi |first=James |url=http://social.entertainment.msn.com/movies/blogs/the-hitlist-blogpost.aspx?post=be05b01c-daff-4954-867c-f58f1337226b|title=Interview: Christopher Plummer of 'The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'|publisher=[[MSN]] |date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> Plummer wanted to imbue the character with [[irony]], an element he found to be absent from the novel's Henrik.<ref name=amm2>{{cite video|date=December 23, 2011|title=The Girl With The Dragon Tattoo - Interview with Christopher Plummer|format=Audio commentary |medium=Dialogue |publisher=[[HitFix]]}}</ref> "I think that the old man would have it," he opined, "because he's a very sophisticated old guy [...] used to a great deal of power. So in dealing with people, he would be very good [...] he would be quite jokey, and know how to seduce them."<ref name=amm2/>
* [[Stellan Skarsg<U+00E5>rd]] as Martin Vanger
:Martin is the current CEO of the Vanger Corporation. Skarsg<U+00E5>rd was allured by the character's dual nature, and was fascinated that he got to portray him in "two totally different ways".<ref name=amm>{{cite video|date=December 18, 2011|title=The Girl With The Dragon Tattoo - Stellan Skarsg<U+00E5>rd interview|format=Audio commentary |medium=Dialogue |publisher=Black Film}} Note: Event occurs at time 0:45-1:04 and 1:39-1:45.</ref> In regards to Martin's "very complex" and "complicated" personality, the Swedish actor said, "He can be extremely charming but he also can seem to be a completely different person at different points in the film."<ref name=filming/> While consulting with Fincher, the director wanted Skarsg<U+00E5>rd to play Martin without reference to the book.<ref name=amm/>
* [[Joely Richardson]] as Anita Vanger / Harriet Vanger
:In performing her "tricky" character, Richardson recalled that Fincher wanted her to embrace a "darker, edgier" persona, without sugarcoating, and not "resolved or healed". "Even if you were starting to move towards the direction of resolved or healed, he still wanted it edgy and dark. There are no straightforward emotions in the world of this film."<ref name=filming/>
* [[Robin Wright]] as Erika Berger
* [[Steven Berkoff]] as Dirch Frode
* [[Geraldine James]] as Cecilia Vanger
* [[Ulf Friberg]] as Wennerstr<U+00F6>m
* [[Goran Vi<U+0161>nji<U+0107>]] as Dragan Armansky
* [[Donald Sumpter]] as Detective Morell
* [[Embeth Davidtz]] as Annika Giannini
* [[Joel Kinnaman]] as Christer Malm
* [[Elodie Yung]] as Miriam Wu
* [[Tony Way]] as Plague
* [[Alan Dale]] as Detective Isaksson
* [[Julian Sands]] as Young Henrik Vanger
* [[David Dencik]] as Young Morell
* [[Fredrik Dolk]] as Wennerstr<U+00F6>m's Lawyer
* [[Per Myrberg]] as Harald Vanger
* [[Gustaf Hammarsten]] as Young Harald
* [[Leo Bill]] as Trinity
* [[Josefin Asplund]] as Pernilla Blomkvist
* [[Matthew Wolf]] as Technical Clerk

== Production ==
===Conception and writing===
The success of Stieg Larsson's novel created Hollywood interest in adapting the book, as became apparent in 2009, when Lynton and Pascal pursued the idea of developing an "American" version unrelated to the [[The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2009 film)|film adaptation released that year]]. By December, two major developments occurred for the project: [[Steven Zaillian]], who had recently completed the script for ''[[Moneyball (film)|Moneyball]]'' (2011), became the screenwriter, while producer [[Scott Rudin]] finalized a partnership allocating full copyrights to Sony.<ref name=hollzgirl/> Zaillian, who was unfamiliar with the novel, got a copy from Rudin. The screenwriter recalled, "They sent it to me and said, 'We want to do this.  We will think of it as one thing for now. It's possible that it can be two and three, but let's concentrate on this one.'"<ref name=collider3>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/steven-zaillian-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-timecrimes-interview/133392/|title=Screenwriter Steven Zaillian Talks THE GIRL WITH THE DRAGON TATTOO, Sequels, and How He Might Direct the Remake of TIMECRIMES|first=Steve|last=Weintraub|publisher=Collider|date=December 26, 2011|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> After reading the book, the screenwriter did no research on the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/feature/2096/steven-zaillian-screenwriting-is-a-lonely-business|title=Steven Zaillian: 'Screenwriting is a lonely business'|last=Jenkins|first=David|work=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out London]]|date=|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> 
Fincher, who was requested with partner Cean Chaffin by Sony executives to read the novel,<ref name=hollzgirl/><ref>{{cite news |last=Harris |first=Scott |url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/04/01/david-fincher-the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo |title=David Fincher Inks Deal For 'Dragon Tattoo'|publisher=[[Moviefone]] |date=April 1, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref>
was astounded by the series' size and success. As they began to read, the duo noticed that it had a tendency to take "readers on a lot of side trips"<U+2014>"from detailed explanations of surveillance techniques to angry attacks on corrupt Swedish industrialists," professed ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'s}} Gregg Kilday. Fincher recalled of the encounter: "The ballistic, ripping-yarn thriller aspect of it is kind of a red herring in a weird way. It is the thing that throws Salander and Blomkvist together, but it is their relationship you keep coming back to. I was just wondering what 350 pages Zaillian would get rid of." Because Zaillian was already cultivating the screenplay, the director avoided interfering. After a conversation, Fincher was comfortable "they were headed in the same direction".<ref name=hollzgirl/>

{{Quote box|quote=I imagined someone who could move through the streets of Stockholm almost invisibly even though she looks the way she looks <U+2026> it's almost like a forcefield|source={{mdash}}Steven Zaillian<ref name=guard/> |width=32% |bgcolor=#CFECEC |salign=right |align = left}}

The writing process consumed approximately six months, including three months creating notes and analyzing the novel.<ref name=collider3/> Zaillian noted that as time progressed, the writing accelerated. "As soon as you start making decisions," he explained, "you start cutting off all of the other possibilities of things that could happen.  So with every decision that you make you are removing a whole bunch of other possibilities of where that story can go or what that character can do."<ref name=collider3/> Given the book's sizable length, Zaillian deleted elements to match Fincher's desired running time.<ref name=collider3/> Even so, Zaillan took significant departures from the book.<ref name= guard/> To Zaillian, there was always a "low-grade" anxiety, "but I was never doing anything specifically to please or displease," he continued. "I was simply trying to tell the story the best way I could, and push that out of my mind. I didn't change anything just for the sake of changing it. There's a lot right about the book, but that part, I thought we could do it a different way, and it could be a nice surprise for the people that have read it."<ref name= guard >{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2011/dec/17/girl-with-dragon-tattoo-steven-zaillian|title=The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo: Steven Zaillian on the difficulties of adapting Stieg Larsson|first=Alex|last=Godfrey|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=December 16, 2011|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref>

Zaillian discussed many of the themes in Larsson's [[Millennium series|''Millennium'' series]] with Fincher, taking the pair deeper into the novel's darker subjects, such as the psychological dissimilarities between rapists and murders.<ref name= guard/> Fincher was familiar with the concept, from projects such as ''[[Seven (film)|Seven]]'' (1995) and ''[[Zodiac (film)|Zodiac]]'' (2007). Zaillian commented, "A rapist, or at least our rapist, is about exercising his power over somebody. A serial killer is about destruction; they get off on destroying something. It's not about having power over something, it's about eliminating it. What thrills them is slightly different."<ref name= guard/> The duo wanted to expose the novels' pivotal themes, particularly [[misogyny]]. "We were committed to the tack that this is a movie about violence against women about specific kinds of degradation, and you can't shy away from that. But at the same time you have to walk a razor thin line so that the audience can viscerally feel the need for revenge but also see the power of the ideas being expressed."<ref name=filming/> Instead of the typical [[three-act structure]], they reluctantly chose a [[act (drama)#Five-act play|five act structure]], which Fincher pointed out is "very similar to a lot of TV [[cop drama]]s."<ref>{{Cite audio |first =David |last=Fincher |year=2012 |title= The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo |type= DVD commentary track |publisher= [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] |time= 10:30{{nbsp}}to 11:10 |timecaption= From || oclc= 776713480 |quote= |}}</ref>

===Filming===
[[File:Stockholm 8187.jpg|thumb|[[Stockholm, Sweden]] provided for much of the setting of ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo''.]]

Fincher and Zaillian's central objective was to maintain the novel's setting. To portray Larsson's vision of Sweden, and the interaction of light on its landscape, Fincher cooperated with an artistic team that included cinematographer [[Jeff Cronenweth]] and production designer [[Donald Graham Burt]]. The film was wholly shot using [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company]]'s RED MX digital camera, chosen to help evoke Larsson's tone. The idea, according to Cronenweth, was to employ unorthodox light sources and maintain a realistic perspective. "So there may be shadows, there may be flaws, but it's reality. You allow silhouettes and darkness, but at the same time we also wanted shots to counter that, so it would not all be one continuous dramatic image."<ref name=filming/> Sweden's climate was a crucial element in enhancing the mood. Cronenweth commented, "It's always an element in the background and it was very important that you feel it as an audience member. The winter becomes like a silent character in the film giving everything a low, cool-colored light that is super soft and non-direct."<ref name=filming/> To get acquainted with Swedish culture, Burt set out on a month-long expedition across the country. He said of the process, "It takes time to start really taking in the nuances of a culture, to start seeing the themes that recur in the architecture, the landscape, the layouts of the cities and the habits of the people. I felt I had to really integrate myself into this world to develop a true sense of place for the film. It was not just about understanding the physicality of the locations, but the metaphysics of them, and how the way people live comes out through design."<ref name=filming/>

[[Principal photography]] began in [[Stockholm, Sweden]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/2010/10/08/finchers_dragon_tattoo_cast_so_far |title=Fincher Calls Girl with 'Dragon Tattoo' Swedish Noir, Adds Cast, as Filming Begins in Stockholm <U+2013> Thompson on Hollywood |date=September 8, 2010|work=[[indieWire]]|publisher=[[Snagfilms]]|accessdate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> Production mostly took place at multiple locations in the city's central business district, including at the [[Stockholm Court House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/har-ar-rooney-mara-som-salander_5482963.svd|title=H<U+00E4>r <U+00E4>r Rooney Mara som Salander|language=Swedish|work=Svenska Dagbladet|publisher=Schibsted|date=October 9, 2010|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> One challenge was realizing the Vanger estate. They picked an eighteenth century [[French architecture]] mansion located a few kilometers southwest of Stockholm. Filmmakers wanted to use a typical "manor from Sm<U+00E5>land" that was solemn, formal, and "very Old Money". "The Swedish are very good at the modern and the minimal but they also have these wonderful country homes that can be juxtaposed against the modern city<U+2014>yet both speak to money."<ref name=filming/> Principal photography relocated in October to [[Uppsala]]. On Queen Street, the facade of the area was renovated to mimic the Hotel Alder, after an old photograph of a building obtained by Fincher.<ref name=svedag>{{cite web|url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/daniel-craig-filmade-i-uppsala_5461189.svd|title=Daniel Craig filmade i Uppsala|language=Swedish|first=Carl|last=Cato|work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|publisher=[[Schibsted]]|date=October 6, 2010|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> From December onward, production moved to [[Zurich, Switzerland]], where locations were established at [[Dolder Grand Hotel]] and the [[Zurich Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zuerich.com/en/zurich-film-office/production-index/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo.html#details|title=The girl with the dragon tattoo|publisher=Zurich Film Office|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> Because of the "beautiful" environment of the city, Fincher found it difficult to film in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zueritipp.ch/kino/kino/-Z-rich-ist-zu-sch-n-zum-Filmen-/story/19283982/|title=Z<U+00DC>RICH IST ZU SCH<U+00D6>N ZUM FILMEN|language=German|first=Andreas|last=Scheiner|work=[[Tages-Anzeiger]]|publisher=[[Tamedia]]|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> Principal photography concluded in [[Oslo, Norway]], where production took place at the [[Oslo Airport, Gardermoen]]. Recorded for over fifteen hours, twelve [[extra (actor)|extras]] were sought for background roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/rampelys/artikkel.php?artid=10092580|title=Hemmelig Hollywood-innspilling i Norge|language=Norwegian|first=Atle|last=Jorstad|work=[[Verdens Gang]]|publisher=[[Schibsted]]|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref>

====Title sequence====
[[file:GirlTattooHotHands.jpeg|thumb|left|In the "Hot Hands" vignette, the rough, gnarled hands caressing Salander's face serves as a metaphor for the atrocities committed by men.]] 

Tim Miller, creative director for the title sequence, wanted to develop an abstract narrative that reflected the pivotal moments in the novel, as well as the character development of Lisbeth Salander. It was arduous for Miller to conceptualize the sequence abstractly, given that Salander's occupation was a distinctive part of her personality. His initial ideas were modeled after a keyboard. "We were going to treat the keyboard like this giant city with massive fingers pressing down on the keys," Miller explained, "Then we transitioned to the liquid going through the giant obelisks of the keys."<ref name=i0/> Among Miller's many vignettes was "The Hacker Inside", which revealed the character's inner disposition and melted them away. The futuristic qualities in the original designs provided for a much more [[cyberpunk]] appearance than the final product. In creating the "cyber" look for Salander, Miller said, "Every time I would show David a design he would say, 'More Tandy!' It's the shitty little computers from Radio Shack, the Tandy computers. They probably had vacuum tubes in them, really old technology. And David would go 'More Tandy', until we ended up with something that looked like we glued a bunch of computer parts found at a junkyard together."<ref name=i0>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/5873372/an-exclusive-look-at-the-making-of-dragon-tattoos-stunning-titles|title=An Exclusive Look at the Making of Dragon Tattoo<U+2019>s Stunning Titles|first=Meredith|last=Woerner|publisher=[[io9]]|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref> 

Fincher wanted the vignette to be a "personal nightmare" for Salander, replaying her darkest moments. "Early on, we knew it was supposed to feel like a nightmare," Miller professed, who commented that early on in the process, Fincher wanted to use an artwork as a template for the sequence. After browsing through various paintings to no avail, Fincher chose a painting that depicted the artist, covered in black paint, standing in the middle of a gallery. Many of Miller's sketches contained a liquid-like component, and were rewritten to produce the "gooey" element that was so desired. "David said let's just put liquid in all of them and it will be this primordial dream ooze that's a part of every vignette," Miller recalled. "It ties everything together other than the black on black."<ref name=i0/>

The title sequence includes abundant references to the novel, and exposes several political themes. Salander's tattoos, such as her phoenix and dragon tattoos, were incorporated. The multiple flower representations signified the biological life cycle, as well as Henrik, who received a banquet of flowers each year on his birthday. "One had flowers coming out of this black ooze," said Fincher, "it blossoms, and then it dies. And then a different flower, as that one is dying is rising from the middle of it. It was supposed to represent this cycle of the killer sending flowers."<ref name=i0/> Ultimately, the vignette becomes very conceptual because Miller and his team took "a whole thought, and cut it up into multiple different shots that are mixed in with other shots". In one instance, Blomkvist is strangled by strips of newspaper, a metaphor for the establishment squelching his exposes.<ref name=i0/>

In the "Hot Hands" vignette, the nefarious actions of men are symbolized as a pair of rough, distorted hands that embrace Salander's face, melting it. These hands, according to Miller, are a metaphor for wealth and power. "They're rich people hands, and with her it's the hands of bad men," Miller avouched.<ref name=i0/> Themes of [[domestic violence]] become apparent as a woman's face shatters after a merciless beating; this also ties in the brutal beating of Salander's mother by her father, an event revealed in the sequel, ''[[The Girl Who Played with Fire]]'' (2006).<ref name=i0/>

A cover of [[Led Zeppelin]]'s "[[Immigrant Song]]" (1970) plays throughout the title sequence. The rendition was produced by soundtrack composers [[Atticus Ross]] and [[Nine Inch Nails]] member [[Trent Reznor]], and features vocals from [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]] lead singer [[Karen O]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Annlee |last=Ellingson |date=December 15, 2011 |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo |publisher=[[Wolfgang's Vault]]| work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/12/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo.html |accessdate=December 22, 2011 }}</ref> Fincher suggested the song, but Reznor agreed only at his request.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Annlee |last=Ellingson |date=December 14, 2011 |title=Trent Reznor: Darkness Audible |work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-dragon-tattoo-trent-reznor-david-fincher-273062 |accessdate=December 22, 2011 }}</ref> Led Zeppelin licensed the song only for use in the film's trailer and title sequence. Fincher stated that he sees title sequences as an opportunity to set the stage for the film, or to get an audience to let go of its preconceptions.<ref>{{cite web |first=Katey |last=Rich |date=December 20, 2011 |title=Dragon Tattoo's Mara, Craig And Fincher Talk Motorcycles And Suffering Take After Take |publisher=[[Cinema Blend]] |url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Dragon-Tattoo-Mara-Craig-Fincher-Talk-Motorcycles-Suffering-Take-Take-28446.html |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>

=== Soundtrack ===
{{Main|The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (soundtrack)}}
{{Quote box |bgcolor=#ffeeaa |salign=right |width=240px |align=right |quote=[The instrumental sounds are] processed and stretched and manipulated into a setting where it may sound harmonically familiar, but if you tune into it, it's not behaving in a way that you're accustomed to that type of sound behaving. I find experimenting around in that is an interesting place to work. |source ={{mdash}}Trent Reznor<ref name="Catsoulis"/>}}

Fincher recruited Reznor and Ross to produce the score; aside from their successful collaboration on ''The Social Network'', the duo had worked together on albums from Nine Inch Nails' later discography.<ref name="Catsoulis"/><ref name=hollzsoundtrack>{{cite web | last=Halperin | first=Shirley | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-dragon-tattoo-trent-reznor-david-fincher-273062| title=Trent Reznor: Darkness Audible| work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 14, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> They dedicated much of the year to work on the film, as they felt it would appeal to a broad audience.<ref name=filmstage>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmstage.com/features/interview-trent-reznor-discusses-the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo/|title=Trent Reznor Discusses <U+2018>The Girl with the Dragon|first=Jack|last=Giroux|date=December 12, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012|publisher=The Film Stage}}</ref> Akin to his efforts in ''The Social Network'', Reznor experiments with [[acoustic music|acoustics]] and blends them with elements of [[electronic music]], resulting in a forbidding atmosphere. "We wanted to create the sound of coldness<U+2014>emotionally and also physically," he asserted, "We wanted to take lots of acoustic instruments [...] and transplant them into a very inorganic setting, and dress the set around them with electronics."<ref name="Catsoulis">{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/2011/12/19/143834396/trent-reznor-the-fresh-air-interview|title=Trent Reznor: The Fresh Air Interview|first=Terry|last=Gross|date=December 19, 2011 |publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> 

Even before viewing the script, Reznor and Ross opted to utilize a redolent approach to creating the film's score. After discussing with Fincher the varying soundscapes and emotions, the duo spent six weeks composing. "We composed music we felt might belong," stated the Nine Inch Nails lead vocalist, "and then we'd run it by Fincher, to see where his head<U+2019>s at and he responded positively. He was filming at this time last year and assembling rough edits of scenes to see what it feels like, and he was inserting our music at that point, rather than using temp music, which is how it usually takes place, apparently." Finding a structure for the soundtrack was arguably the most strenuous task. "We weren<U+2019>t working on a finished thing, so everything keeps moving around, scenes are changing in length, and even the order of things are shuffled around, and that can get pretty frustrating when you get precious about your work. It was a lesson we learned pretty quickly of, 'Everything is in flux, and approach it as such. Hopefully it<U+2019>ll work out in the end.'"<ref name=filmstage/>

==Release==
===Pre-release===
[[File:Rooney Mara, Daniel Craig and David Fincher (2012).jpg|thumb|Mara, Craig, and Fincher at the French premiere of ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' in Paris.]]

A screening for ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' took place on November 28, 2011, as part of a critics-only event hosted by the [[New York Film Critics Circle]]. Commentators at the event predicted that while the film would become a contender for several accolades, it would likely not become a forerunner in the pursuit for [[Academy Award]] nominations.<ref name="tops">{{cite web | last=Dickey | first=Josh | url=http://weblogs.variety.com/thevote/2011/11/dragon-tattoo-finally-screens-awards-await-but-not-a-game-changer.html| title='Dragon Tattoo' finally screens: Awards await, but 'Not a game-changer'| publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]| work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012 }}</ref> A promotional campaign commenced thereafter, including a Lisbeth Salander-inspired collection, designed by Trish Summerville for [[H&M]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2011/12/02/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-hm-collection/|title=H&M Releases Images Of The 'Girl With The Dragon Tattoo' Collection|first=Gaby|last=Wilson|date=December 2, 2011 |publisher=MTV (Viacom)|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2011/12/20/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-marketing/|title=Stieg Larsson's partner chides 'Dragon Tattoo' marketing|date=December 20, 2011 |publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> The worldwide premiere was at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] in [[London]] on December 12, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a355520/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-premieres-in-london-pictures.html|title='The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo' premieres in London - pictures|date=December 12, 2011 |first|Simon|last=Reynolds|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> followed by the American opening at the [[Ziegfeld Theatre]] in [[New York City]] on December 14 and Stockholm the next day.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-premiere-photos-rooney-mara-daniel-craig-273909| title='The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo' Premiere: Rooney Mara, Daniel Craig Hit the Red Carpet (Photos)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 14, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2011/12/15/rooney-mara-dragon-tattoo-cutout-dress/|title=Rooney Mara Premieres 'The Girl With The Dragon Tattoo' In Nothing But Cutout Outfits|first=Andi|last=Teran|date=December 15, 2011 |publisher=MTV (Viacom)|accessdate=July 3, 2012}}</ref> Sony's target demographics were men and women over the age of 25 and 17<U+2013>34.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-preview-christmas-girl-with-dragon-tattoo-275851| title=Box Office Preview: The Christmas Cavalcade Begins, But Will Moviegoers Turn Up?|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 20, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The film went into general release in North America on December 21, at 2,700 theaters,<ref name=hollzoffice>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-with-dragon-tattoo-box-office-opening-275904| title=Box Office Report: 'Girl with the Dragon Tattoo' Grosses at Least $1.6 Mil in Tuesday Night Runs|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 14, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> expanding to 2,974 theaters on its second day.<ref name=hollzoffice/> The United Kingdom release was on December 26,<ref name=hollzoffice2>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-war-horse-spielberg-277144| title=Foreign Box Office: 'Mission:Impossible -- Ghost Protocol' Remains No. 1 Overseas for Third Consecutive Stanza|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 1, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> Russia on January 1, 2012,<ref name=hollzoffice5>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-sherlock-holmes-mission-impossible-279501| title=Foreign Box Office: Second 'Sherlock Holmes' Dethrones Fourth 'Mission: Impossible' As No. 1 Attraction Overseas|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 8, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> and Japan on February 13.<ref name=jpn>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-dragon-tattoo-opens-big-japan-291259| title='The Girl With The Dragon Tattoo' Opens Big In Japan|first=Gavin|last=Blair|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=February 15, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> India and Vietnam releases were abandoned due to cencorship concerns.<ref name=hollzviet>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/girl-dragon-tattoo-withdrawn-release-290073| title=<U+2018>The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo<U+2019> Withdrawn From Release in Vietnam|first=Michael|last=Mackey|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name=guard22>{{cite web| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/jan/30/girl-dragon-tattoo-cancelled-india| title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo cancelled in India|first=Ben|last=Child|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News & Media| date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> A press statement from the [[Central Board of Film Certification]] stated: "Sony Pictures will not be releasing The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo in India. The censor board has judged the film unsuitable for public viewing in its unaltered form and, while we are committed to maintaining and protecting the vision of the director, we will, as always, respect the guidelines set by the board."<ref name=guard22/> In contrast, the National Film Board of Vietnam insisted that the film's withdrawal had no relation to rigid censorship guidelines, as it had not been reviewed by the committee.<ref name=hollzviet/>

===Box office===
Fincher's film grossed $232.6 million during its theatrical run.<ref name="Box Office" /> The film's American release grossed $1.6M from its Tuesday night screenings,<ref name=hollzoffice/> a figure that increased to $3.5M by the end of its first day of general release.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-ghost-protocol-box-office-276048| title=Box Office Report: Tom Cruise's 'Mission: Impossible 4' Shoots to No. 1|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 22, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> It maintained momentum into its opening weekend, accumulating $13M for a total of $21M in domestic revenue.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mission-impossible-tom-cruise-box-office-276309|title=Box Office Report: 'Mission: Impossible 4' Christmas Victor, Tom Cruise is Back|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 25, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The film's debut figures fell below media expectations.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-12-28/news/30566850_1_r-rated-movies-dragon-tattoo-s-pg-13| title=<U+2018>Girl With Dragon Tattoo<U+2019> sequels a mystery|first=Ethan|last=Sacks|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]| date=December 28, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/12/26/dragon-tattoo-box-office/|title='The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo': Lots of hype, but weak box office. What gives?|date=December 26, 2011 |first=Laura|last=Hertzfeld|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/04/us-dragontattoo-sequel-idUSTRE80303J20120104|title=Despite poor box office, "Dragon Tattoo" sequel moves ahead|date=January 3, 2012|first=Kurt|last=Orzeck|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> However, aided by positive [[word of mouth]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/12/box-office-dragon-tattoo-mission-impossible.html| title=Box Office: 'Girl With the Dragon Tattoo' has aggressive launch|first=Amy|last=Kaufman|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]| date=December 21, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> its commercial performance remained steady into the second week, posting $19M from 2,914 theaters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mission-impossible-tom-cruise-war-horse-box-office-277222|title=Box Office Report: Tom Cruise's 'M:I 4' Big Holiday Victor, Earns $366.5 Mil|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 2, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The third week saw box office drop 24% to $11.3M, totaling $76.8M. The number of theaters slightly increased to 2,950.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-report-devil-inside-279481|title=Box Office Report: 'The Devil Inside' Opens to Record Breaking $34.5 Mil|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 8, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> By the fifth week, the number of theaters shrank to 1,907, and grosses to $3.7M, though it remained within the national top ten.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-report-underworld-4-red-tails-283856|title=Box Office Report: 'Underworld 4' Nabs $25.4 Mil, 'Red Tails' Overperforms With $19.1 Mil|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 22, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The film completed its North American theatrical run on March 22, 2012, earning over $102.5M.<ref name="Box Office" />

The international debut was in six Scandinavian markets on December 19<U+2013>25, 2011, securing $1.6M from 480 venues.<ref name=hollzoffice22>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-mission-impossible-ghost-protocol-276307| title= Foreign Box Office: 'Mission: Impossible - Ghost Protocol' Finishes in Top Spot for Second Straight Weekend|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=December 26, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> In Sweden the film opened in 194 theaters to strong results, accounting for more than half of international revenue at the time ($950,000).<ref name=hollzoffice22/> The first full week in the United Kingdom collected $6.7M from 920 theaters.<ref name=hollzoffice2/> By the weekend of January 6<U+2013>8, 2012, the film grossed $12.2M for a total of $29M; this included its expansion into Hong Kong, where it topped the box office, earning $470,000 from thirty-six establishments. The film similarly led the field in South Africa. It accumulated $6.6M from an estimated 600 theaters over a seven day period in Russia, placing fifth.<ref name=hollzoffice5/> The expansion continued into the following week, opening in nine markets. The week of January 13<U+2013>15 saw the film yield $16.1M from 3,910 locations in over forty-three territories, thus propelling the foreign gross to $49.3M.<ref name=hollzoffice222/> It debuted at second place in Austria and Germany, where in the latter, it pulled $2.9M from 525 locations.<ref name=hollzoffice222>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-sherlock-holmes-contraband-mission-impossible-282011| title= Foreign Box Office: 'Sherlock Holmes: A Game Of Shadows' Still No. 1 Overseas|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 15, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> Similar results were achieved in Australia, where it reached 252 theaters.<ref name=hollzoffice222/> The film's momentum continued throughout the month, and by January 22, it had hit ten additional markets, including France and Mexico, from which it drew $3.25M from 540 venues and $1.25M from 540 theaters, respectively.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-sherlock-holmes-underworld-awakening-283874| title=Foreign Box Office: 'Sherlock Holmes: A Game Of Shadows' Hangs on as No. 1 for Third Straight Weekend|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 22, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> In its second week in France it descended to number three, with a total gross of $5.8M.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-mission-impossible-ghost-protocol-descendants-grey-285524| title=Foreign Box Office: 'Mission: Impossible--Ghost Protocol' Retakes Top Spot; 'Descendants' Jumps to No. 4|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=January 29, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> 

The next major international release came in Japan on February 13, where it opened in first place with $3.68M (<U+00A5>288M)<ref name=jpn/> in 431 theaters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-journey-star-wars-289703| title=Foreign Box Office: 'Journey 2' Outpoints 'Star Wars' Reissue, Seizes No. 1 Spot Overseas|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=February 12, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> By the weekend of February 17<U+2013>19, the film had scooped up $119.5M from foreign markets.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-journey-2-this-means-war-292645| title=Foreign Box Office: 'Journey 2' Repeats as No. 1 Overseas|first=Frank|last=Segers|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| date=February 19, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The total international gross for ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' was $130.1M.<ref name="Box Office" /> MGM, one of the studios involved in the production, posted a "modest loss" and declared that they had expected the film to gross at least 10% more.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo director lashes out at US remake |first=David |last=Lieberman |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/mgm-takes-a-loss-on-dragon-tattoo-and-seeks-better-terms-for-sequels/ |publisher=Deadline |date=March 22, 2012 |accessdate=June 6, 2012}}</ref>

=== Home media ===
[[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] released the film in a [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] disc combo pack in the United States on March 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flixster.com/movie/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo/ |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo |publisher=[[Flixster]]|date=December 20, 2011|accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Bonus features include a commentary from Fincher, featurettes on Blomkvist, Salander, the sets and locations, etc.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whitman|first=Howard|title=Blu-ray Review: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2011)|url=http://www.technologytell.com/hometech/84352/blu-ray-review-the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-2011/|publisher=Technologytell|accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref> The disc artwork for the [[DVD-Video]] version of the film resembles a [[Sony]] brand [[DVD-R]], a reference to the hacker Lisbeth Salander. This caused a bit of confusion in the marketplace with consumers thinking they had obtained a [[bootleg recording|bootleg]] copy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Girl With The Dragon Tattoo original DVD looks like a bootleg copy|publisher=Ubergizmo|url=http://www.ubergizmo.com/2012/03/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-original-dvd-looks-like-a-bootleg-copy/|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=<U+2018>Girl With the Dragon Tattoo<U+2019> Bootleg Packaging Fools Consumers|publisher=Mashable|url=http://mashable.com/2012/03/22/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-dvd/|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The release sold 644,000 copies in its first week, in third place behind ''[[The Muppets (film)|The Muppets]]'' and ''[[Hop (film)|Hop]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=7162|title=DVD Sales: Muppets Show How it's Done|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=April 3, 2012|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The following week, the film sold an additional 144,000 copies generating $2.59 million in gross revenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=7175|title=DVD Sales: Alvin Hops to the Top|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> As of July, 2012, 1,049,812 units had been sold, grossing $18.8 million.<ref name="dvdsales">{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2011/TGRLW-DVD.php|title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo - DVD Sales|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Critical response===
[[File:Rooney Mara 2012.jpg|thumb|Mara's portrayal of Lisbeth Salander attracted critical acclaim from commentators.]]

Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 87% of commentators gave the film a positive review, based on 212 professional critiques. With a mean score of 7.6/10, the site's consensus stated, "Brutal yet captivating, ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' is the result of David Fincher working at his lurid best with total role commitment from star Rooney Mara."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_girl_with_the_dragon_tattoo/ |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2011) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 based on the reviews of mainstream critics, the received an average score of 71 based on 41 reviews.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-2011/critic-reviews| title = Critic Reviews for The Girl with The Dragon Tattoo (2011)| date = January 3, 2012| accessdate = January 3, 2012| publisher = [[Metacritic]]}}</ref>

[[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' asserted that the austere, but captivating installment presented a "glancing, chilled view" of a world where succinct moments of loyalty coexisted with constant trials of betrayal.<ref name="Denby">{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2011/12/12/111212crci_cinema_denby |title=Double Dare |author=Denby, David |work=[[The New Yorker]] |publisher=Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications|date=December 5, 2011 |accessdate=December 13, 2011}}</ref> To ''[[USA Today]]'' columnist Claudia Puig, Fincher captures the "menace and grim despair in the frosty Scandinavian landscape" by carefully approaching its most gruesome features.<ref name=usa>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/story/2011-12-19/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo/52083012/1?csp=34life&utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+UsatodaycomMovies-TopStories+%28Life+-+Movies+-+Top+Stories%29|title=David Fincher's 'Dragon Tattoo' has style to burn|last=Puig|first=Claudia|date=December 19, 2011|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Puig noted a surfeit of "stylistic flourishes" and "intriguing" changes in the narrative, compared to the original film.<ref name=usa/> In his three-and-a-half star review, Chris Knight of the ''[[National Post]]'' argued that it epitomized a so-called "paradoxical position" that was both "immensely enjoyable and completely unnecessary".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arts.nationalpost.com/2011/12/20/review-david-fincher-makes-his-mark-with-the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo/ |title=Review: David Fincher makes his mark with The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo|first=Chris|last=Knight|work=[[National Post]]|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|date=December 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Rene Rodriguez of ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' said that the "fabulously sinister entertainment" surpassed the original film "in every way".<ref name=mias>{{cite web|url=http://www.miami.com/039the-girl-dragon-tattoo039-r-article|title='The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo' (R)|last=Rodriguez|first=Rene|date=December 20, 2011|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|publisher=David Landsberg|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The film took two-and-a-half stars from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commentator Peter Travers, who concluded: "Fincher's ''Girl'' is gloriously rendered but too impersonal to leave a mark."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-20111222|title=The Girl With The Dragon Tattoo|first=Peter|last=Travers|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Jann Wenner|date=December 22, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]], writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', admired the moments of "brilliantly orchestrated" anxiety and confusion, but felt that ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' was not invulnerable to the "lumbering proceduralism" that he saw in its literary counterpart, as evident with the "long stretches of drab, hackneyed exposition that flatten the atmosphere".<ref name="Dargis">{{cite web|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/2011/12/20/movies/the-girl-with-dragon-tattoo-movie-review.html?pagewanted=1|title=The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo (2011)|last=Scott |first=A. O. |date=December 19, 2011 | work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''{{'s}} [[Joe Morgenstern]] praised Cronenweth's cinematography, which he thought provided for glossy alterations in the film's darkness; "Stockholm glitters in nighttime exteriors, and its subway shines in a spectacular spasm of action involving a backpack."<ref name=wsj>{{cite web | url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204552304577114432341153856.html| title='Tattoo': Raw, Rousing and Rather Redundant| publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]| work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=December 23, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012 | author=Morgenstern, Joe}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] of ''[[The New York Observer]]'' professed that despite its occasional incomprehensibility, the movie was "technically superb" and "superbly acted".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://observer.com/2011/12/girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo-is-quite-the-swedish-dish/|title=Girl With the Dragon Tattoo is Quite the Swedish Dish|first=Rex|last=Reed| |publisher=[[Jared Kushner]]|work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=December 14, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> In contrast, Kyle Smith of ''[[New York Post]]'' censured the film, calling it "rubbish" and further commenting that it "demonstrates merely that masses will thrill to an unaffecting, badly written, psychologically shallow and deeply unlikely pulp story so long as you allow them to feel sanctified by the occasional meaningless reference to feminism or Nazis."<ref name="KyleSmith">{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/glaring_problems_BgF3snZsIUAA2fMATM74YL |title=Glaring problems |author=Smith, Kyle |publisher=Paul Carlucci|work=[[New York Post]] |date=December 19, 2011 |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>

The performances were a frequent topic in the critiques. Mara's performance, in particular, was admired by commentators. In comparing the performances between Mara and [[Noomi Rapace]], who played Salander in the [[The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2009 film)|2009 film]], [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' said that Rapace felt more self-conscious in the role.<ref name="Ebert">{{cite web |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20111219/REVIEWS/111219982/1001 |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo |author=Ebert, Roger |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]| date=December 19, 2011 |accessdate=December 19, 2011}}</ref> A revelation in the eyes of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} [[Owen Gleiberman]], he proclaimed that her character was more important than "her ability to solve a crime".<ref name="Gleiberman">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20483133_20518628,00.html |title=The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo |author=Gleiberman, Owen |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=Time Inc.|date=December 13, 2011 |accessdate=December 13, 2011}}</ref> Her "hypnotic" portrayal was noticed by Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title = The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo review |first = Justin |last = Chang |url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117946739 |work = Variety |publisher = Reed Business Information |date = December 13, 2011 |accessdate = January 17, 2012}}</ref> as well as ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' critic Andrew O'Hehir, who wrote, "Rooney Mara is a revelation as Lisbeth Salander, the damaged, aggressive computer geek and feminist revenge angel, playing the character as far more feral and vulnerable than Noomi Rapace<U+2019>s borderline-stereotype sexpot Goth girl."<ref name="O'Hehir">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/12/20/the_girl_with_the_dragon_tattoo_a_bigger_darker_swedish_nightmare/singleton/|title=<U+201C>The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo<U+201D>: A bigger, darker Swedish nightmare|last=O'Hehir |first=Andrew |date=December 20, 2011 | work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|publisher=Salon Media Group|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Scott Tobias of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' enjoyed the chemistry between Mara and Craig,<ref>{{cite web |title = The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo review |first = Scott |last = Tobias |url = http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-girl-with-the-dragon-tattoo,66849/ |work = [[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]]||date = December 20, 2011 |accessdate = January 17, 2012}}</ref> as did David Germain of the [[Associated Press]]; "Mara and Craig make an indomitable screen pair, he nominally leading their intense search into decades-old serial killings, she surging ahead, plowing through obstacles with flashes of phenomenal intellect and eruptions of physical fury."<ref name="Germain">{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2011/12/13/review_dragon_tattoo_kicks_proverbial_butt/?rss_id=Boston.com+--+Movie+news |title=Review: 'Dragon Tattoo' kicks proverbial butt |author=Germain, David |publisher=Associated Press |date=December 13, 2011 |accessdate=December 13, 2011}}</ref>  Puig found Mara inferior to Rapace in playing Salander, though to her, Mara evoked a fragility that undermined the character's more vocal acts of defiance.<ref name=usa/> In regards to Craig's performance, Puig said that the actor shone, a view that was shared with Morgenstern, who avouched that Craig "nonetheless finds welcome humor in Mikael's impassive affect".<ref name=wsj/>

=== Accolades ===
In addition to numerous awards, ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' was included on several year-end lists by film commentators and publications. It was named the best film of 2011 by [[MTV]] and [[James Berardinelli]] of ''ReelViews''.<ref name=mtv33/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelthoughts.php?identifier=683|title=Rewinding 2011: The Top 10|first=James|last=Beradinelli|work=ReelViews|date=December 31, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The former wrote, "The director follows up the excellent ''Social Network'' with another tour de force, injecting the murder mystery that introduces us to outcast hacker Lisbeth Salander [...] and embattled journalist [...] with style, intensity and relentless suspense. Mara is a revelation, and the film's daunting 160-minute runtime breezes by thanks to one heart-racing scene after the next. Dark and tough to watch at times, but a triumph all around."<ref name=mtv33>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1676150/best-movies-of-2011.jhtml|title=Best Movies Of 2011|date=December 16, 2011 |publisher=MTV (Viacom)|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The film came second in ''[[indieWire]]''{{'s}} list of "Drew Taylor's Favorite Films Of 2011",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/drew-taylors-favorite-films-of-2011#|title=Drew Taylor's Favorite Films Of 2011|first=Drew|last=Taylor|date=December 24, 2011|work=indieWire|publisher=Snagfilms|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> while reaching the top ten of seven other publications,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.metacritic.com/feature/movie-critic-best-of-2011-top-ten-lists| title =Critics pick the best movies of 2011| date =  December 8, 2011| accessdate = July 5, 2012| publisher = Metacritic}}</ref> including the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/movies/a-second-take-on-the-year-s-best-films/article_72a86954-4fb7-5a01-a99e-a71a26f205e1.html|title=A second take on the year's best films|first=Calvin|last=Wilson|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |publisher=Kevin Mowbray|date=December 31, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'',<Ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Movies-The-Artist-tops-Mick-LaSalle-s-2011-list-2420465.php|title=Movies: 'The Artist' tops Mick LaSalle's 2011 list|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=December 25, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> and the ''[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/movies/index.ssf/2011/12/times-picayune_movie_critic_mi.html|title=Times-Picayune movie critic Mike Scott reveals his list of the Top 10 Films of 2011|first=Mike|last=Scott|work=[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]] |publisher=Ashton Phelps Jr.|date=December 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> ''The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo'' was declared one of the best films of the year by the [[American Film Institute]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/default.aspx|title=AFI Awards 2011|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> as well as the [[National Board of Review of Motion Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/2011NBRAwardsAnnounced.cfm|title=Named 2011 Best Film of the Year by the National Board of Review|publisher=[[National Board of Review of Motion Pictures]]|date=December 1, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>

